  danzasUrbanas_breadcrumb_home: 'Home',
  danzasUrbanas_breadcrumb_classes: 'Dance Classes in Barcelona',
  danzasUrbanas_breadcrumb_current: 'Urban Dance',
  danzasUrbanas_h1: 'Urban Dance in Barcelona: Find Your Style',
  danzasUrbanas_intro:
    "At Farray's Center you train Dancehall, Hip Hop, Twerk, Reggaeton, Heels and more with the exclusive Farray Method® created by Yunaisy Farray (Street Dance 2 dancer) and specialist teachers who teach you from the basics: musicality, coordination, energy, presence… and Flow, lots of flow. Get in shape, release stress and enjoy a sports activity that does NOT bore: every class is different, dynamic and full of good vibes.",

  // What is Urban Dance Section
  danzasUrbanas_whatIs_title: 'What is Urban Dance?',
  danzasUrbanas_whatIs_definition:
    'Urban dances are dance styles born in the streets, plazas and neighborhoods of different cities around the world. They\'re called "urban" because they emerged outside theaters and academies: in the Bronx (Hip Hop), Jamaica (Dancehall), South Korea (K-Pop), Cuba (Reggaeton), Ghana and Nigeria (Afrobeat), and in nightclubs worldwide (Heels, Twerk, Sexy Style).',
  danzasUrbanas_whatIs_origin:
    'The term "urban dance" groups a huge family of styles that share common DNA: they were born from popular culture, transmitted by imitation in the streets and evolved with contemporary urban music (rap, reggae, dancehall, trap, afrobeats). Unlike classical dance (ballet, contemporary, jazz), urban dances prioritize groove, musicality, attitude and personal expression over academic technique.',
  danzasUrbanas_whatIs_difference_title:
    'Difference between "Urban Dance", "Street Dance" and "Commercial Dance"',
  danzasUrbanas_whatIs_difference_urban:
    'Urban Dance: Generic term for all dance styles born in urban and street contexts. Includes Hip Hop, Breaking, Popping, Locking, Krump, House, Dancehall, Afrobeat, etc.',
  danzasUrbanas_whatIs_difference_street:
    'Street Dance: Refers specifically to styles originally danced in the street and in battles (cyphers). E.g.: Breaking, Popping, Locking, Krump. These styles have battle codes, improvisation (freestyle) and competition.',
  danzasUrbanas_whatIs_difference_commercial:
    'Commercial Dance: Urban style choreographed and polished for the entertainment industry: music videos, concerts, TV shows. Mixes technique from different urban styles with elements of jazz, contemporary and commercial influences. E.g.: K-Pop choreographies, Heels, mainstream artist music videos.',
  danzasUrbanas_whatIs_why_many_styles:
    'So many different styles exist because each was born in a unique cultural, geographical and musical context. Hip Hop emerged in the Bronx, New York with rap culture and breakdancing. Dancehall was born in Jamaica with soundsystems and reggae music. K-Pop evolved in South Korea fusing Western pop with Asian aesthetics. Afrobeat connects with modern African rhythms from Ghana, Nigeria and South Africa. Each style tells a different story, has its own codes and is danced with distinct energy.',

  // Which Style to Choose Section
  danzasUrbanas_whichStyle_title: 'Which Urban Style to Choose? Find Your Perfect Dance',
  danzasUrbanas_whichStyle_intro:
    "Each urban style has its own personality, energy and unique benefits. Use this guide to discover which class best suits what you're looking for. There are no wrong answers: you can combine multiple styles and explore freely.",
  danzasUrbanas_whichStyle_tableHeader_goal: "If you're looking for…",
